        description: "Compiègne, imperial city on the edge of the largest forest in Île-de-France, is 1h45 from Lille via the A1.",
        routeDescription: "The route takes the A1 (Northern Motorway) towards Paris to the Compiègne exit, crossing the Artois and Picardy.",
        introduction: "Compiègne is a royal and imperial city nestled between the Oise river and one of France's largest forests — 14,500 hectares of oak, beech and hornbeam that formed the favourite hunting grounds of French sovereigns. The Palace of Compiègne, one of three great royal residences alongside Versailles and Fontainebleau, is a grandiose monument remodelled by Louis XV then by Napoleon I and Napoleon III. Empress Eugénie organised the famous 'Compiègne Series' here, lavish receptions gathering the European elite. The palace now houses three museums: the Historic Apartments (sumptuous Empire furniture), the Second Empire Museum (paintings, sculptures and art objects) and the National Museum of Carriages and Tourism (a unique collection of royal coaches, carriages and early automobiles). But Compiègne is also marked by History with a capital H: the Rethondes Clearing in the Forest of Compiègne is where the Armistice of 11 November 1918 was signed, ending the First World War. A museum wagon, a replica of Marshal Foch's wagon, occupies the exact spot of the signing. It was also in this same clearing that Hitler imposed the armistice on France on 22 June 1940, in a sinister historical symmetry. The forest itself offers exceptional walks: the Beaux Monts, a 4 km bridle path laid out for Napoleon, offers a unique perspective on the palace.",
